          <physDesc>
            <objectDesc>
              <supportDesc material="parchment">
                <support>
                  <p>Fol. <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/en/verse-navigator/sura/26/verse/225/manuscripts/1274/page/1r">1 recto</ref> is hair side, fol. 1 verso is flesh side. </p>
                  <p>Text division: Simple  verse separator consists of a group of three strokes arranged one above  the other in the shape of an arrow. Tenth verse separator is  illuminated with gold, red and brown ink in a round ornament. The end of the Sūrāh 26<hi rend="italic"> aš-šuʿarāʾ</hi> and the beginning of the Sūrāh 27 <hi rend="italic">an-naml </hi>on the fol. 1 r is marked with the name of the new Sūrāh and the number of verses in golden letters.  </p>
                </support>
                <extent>Folios: 1
                                    <dimensions unit="mm"><width>195</width><height>259</height></dimensions>
                                </extent>
              </supportDesc>
              <layoutDesc>
                <layout writtenLines="16">16 - 16 lines to a page
                                </layout>
              </layoutDesc>
            </objectDesc>
            <handDesc>
              <handNote/>
            </handDesc>
            <scriptDesc>
              <summary>
                                Script: Kūfī type B.II according to the palaeographical classification of François Déroche from 1992 <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/QJQEKNSJ" sameAs="QJQEKNSJ" type="zotero">(Déroche 1992: PN 38-39)</ref>. The letter <hi rend="italic">ʾalif </hi>is always vertical, with short return at the baseline in the independent form. The characteristic shape of the letter <hi rend="italic">qāf </hi>in the final position is given with its ending going far to the right. The <hi rend="italic">mašq</hi>-method, the elongation of the horizontal components of the script, is used in the manuscript. Vocalisation is made by red dots. Diacritical marks are used sparsely, originally only the letter <hi rend="italic">nūn </hi>in the independent position is being marked with a dash.
                            </summary>
              <scriptNote>
                                                                kūfī B.II
                            </scriptNote>
            </scriptDesc>
